While it looks like your eventlistener is starting threads it actually doesn&#39;t start any threads!

`MyCustomThread` overrides `Thread.start()` and that means that `t.start()` **does not** start a new thread - it just calls `MyCustomThread.start()` (the &quot;magic&quot; of starting a new thread happens because `Thread.start()` internally calls a native method that creates and starts a new thread, not because the method is called &quot;start&quot;).

This is one of the reasons why you should **never** (well, almost never) subclass `Thread`.

The following adapted code will create threads that you might be able to see:

    @SpringBootApplication
    public class PocApplication {
        
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            SpringApplication.run(PocApplication.class, args);
        }
    
        @EventListener(ApplicationReadyEvent.class)
        public void on() {
            for (int i=0; i &lt;= 50; i++) {
                System.out.println(&quot;Start creating a new thread&quot;);
                Thread t = new Thread(new MyCustomTask(), &quot;test-&quot; + i);
                t.start();
            }
        }
    }
    
    class MyCustomTask implements Runnable {
    
        @Override
        public void run() {
            System.out.println(&quot;Running&quot;);
            try {
                Thread.sleep(20_000);
            } catch (InterruptedException e) {
                throw new RuntimeException(e);
            }
        }
    }

Note that I also increased the sleep time - otherwise those threads will all terminate after just one second which might be too short to observe those threads.

