The problem is not with your URL having dots(.) in its path name, but in Spring SecurityFilterChain, while matching URLs, the `**` is taken to be as a wildcard, depicting that &#39;anything that follows this&#39;. For example, assume

    http
         .authorizeHttpRequests( url -&gt;  url
         .requestMatchers(&quot;odata/v4/**&quot;).authenticated()
         .anyRequest().denyAll())

means that any URL starting with `odata/v4/` and whatever might follow after it is going to be matched by that matcher, and will be processed as mentioned. Therefore, if you are going to manually specify anything after `**` that does not have any precise meaning. Which is exactly why you are seeing this error.

    org.springframework.web.util.pattern.PatternParseException: No more pattern data allowed after {*...} or ** pattern element

If you want to not get this error, remove the `/Handle` after your code to make it look like this

    public SecurityFilterChain filterChain(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
        try{

            http
                    .authorizeHttpRequests( url -&gt;  url
                            .requestMatchers(&quot;/**&quot;).authenticated()
                            .anyRequest().denyAll())
                    .sessionManagement(session -&gt; session.sessionCreationPolicy(SessionCreationPolicy.STATELESS))
                    .oauth2ResourceServer(
                            oauth -&gt; oauth.jwt(jwt -&gt; jwt.jwtAuthenticationConverter(getJwtAuthenticationConverter()))
                    ).headers(httpSecurityHeadersConfigurer -&gt; httpSecurityHeadersConfigurer
                            .contentSecurityPolicy(contentSecurityPolicyConfig -&gt; contentSecurityPolicyConfig
                                    .policyDirectives(CONTENT_SECURITY_POLICY)))
            ;
            return http.build();

    } catch(Exception e){
            throw new RuntimeException(&quot;Authentication is failed&quot;);
        }
    }

this will work, but this will make EVERY request being made to your server to be matched by that matcher, which in turn wants the request to be authenticated, since you are matching every request of the base URL and anything that follows it. If that is what you want, then you have your answer, else you can add the pattern you want to match exactly as it is to the requestMatcher, to have specific requests to be authenticated.

If you want to only allow `http://localhost:8081/odata/v4/com.sap.di.remoteHandler.RemoteHandlerServices/Handle` then you should have 

    .requestMatchers(&quot;odata/v4/com.sap.di.remoteHandler.RemoteHandlerServices/Handle&quot;).authenticated().anyRequest().denyAll())



Hope you got your answer.

