The error message you&#39;re encountering, &quot;Couldn&#39;t find any of the CDI or Jakarta CDI Dependency types,&quot; suggests that there is a conflict or missing configuration related to CDI (Contexts and Dependency Injection) in your project.

As of Hibernate 6, CDI is a required part of the core Hibernate framework. If you&#39;re encountering this error, it likely indicates that there is a compatibility issue with your setup, such as:

1. Dependency Conflicts: There might be conflicting versions of CDI or related libraries in your classpath.

2. Missing Dependency: Your project might be missing the appropriate CDI or Jakarta CDI dependencies.

To address this issue, you can below the below steps:

1. Gradle provides a useful plugin called &quot;Dependency Insights&quot; that helps you analyze and visualize dependency conflicts. To use this plugin, add the following to your `build.gradle`
```
plugins {
    id &quot;com.gradle.plugin-publish&quot; version &quot;0.16.1&quot; // Required for some plugins to work
    id &quot;com.github.ben-manes.versions&quot; version &quot;0.36.0&quot;
}

```

After applying the plugin, you can run below command:
```
./gradlew dependencyInsight --dependency conflicting-module

```

2. If you need to force a specific version of a dependency to resolve conflicts, you can use the resolutionStrategy in your `build.gradle` file like below:
```
configurations.all {
    resolutionStrategy.force &#39;com.example:conflicting-module:desired-version&#39;
}
```

3. You may also consider excluding a specific transitive dependency in your build.gradle like below:

```
implementation (group: &#39;org.hibernate.orm&#39;, name: &#39;hibernate-core&#39;, version: &#39;6.2.7.Final&#39;) {
    exclude group: &#39;javax.enterprise&#39;, module: &#39;cdi-api&#39;
}

```

That should most hopefully resolve your issue. Please do let me know if the issue still persists.

